node.text:
Cannabis Mogul Taks Embracing Mistakes and Building a Business With Your Own Hands

Beth Stavola was one of the first women in the legal marijuana industry who launched and led a multi-state growing manufacturing retail operation in the United States. From there, she went on to the C-Suite role, where she leveraged billion dollar mergers. She truly is a pioneer in the industry, a Wall Street Woman and a mother of six kids. Beth talks about challenges she has faced in business including finding the right operator, and how she turns them into learning lessons. She speaks about her passion to push forward for the rights of women and marginalized communities in politics, business, cannabis, and what she is seeing today in cannabis and brand building that has caught her.

node.text:
Legalization efforts continue on a federal level. @usatoday has a series of articles tracking the progression. Recently Senator Chuck Schumer spoke with @theviewabc on these efforts:

Excerpt from @marijuanamoment
article:
Senate Majority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-NY) on Thursday discussed his strategy for getting enough votes to pass his federal marijuana legalization bill, describing the process of soliciting feedback on the legislation from colleagues and working to incorporate any requested “modifications” in order to get the measure across the finish line.
It was just last week that Schumer unveiled a 163-page draft version of the reform legislation alongside Senate Finance Committee Chairman Ron Wyden (D-OR) and Sen. Cory Booker (D-NJ). While they made clear that public input is valued—and they’ve created an email account where people can submit comments until September 30 on the proposal—the new comments provide a fresh insight into the legislative process to build support for the measure within the Senate.
“We’re now going around to our colleagues saying, ‘Would you sign onto the bill? And if you don’t like what’s in the bill and want some modifications, tell us,'” he told ABC’s The View. “I want to get this done. And I think we will get it done because it’s so, so overwhelmingly supported by the American people.”

node.text:
We acknowledge the concerns regarding our Instagram post of a Forbes.com article featuring Olympic soccer star Megan Rapinoe and her hemp CBD company. We quickly removed it upon the realization that its optics were not as intended.

We thank our followers and critics for holding us accountable, as we are not immune to miscommunication. Along the way, the posted photo and quote, which we pulled directly from a Forbes article to spark conversation, were attributed to our organization.

We took for granted that, through social media, our reach is far beyond the cannabis industry, where there is an understanding of nuances surrounding hemp & cannabis. At the same time, we know this nuance is systemically weaponized by those benefiting from the War on Drugs.

Women Grow has always been and will continue to be an advocate for the legalization of all aspects of the cannabis plant as a pathway to restorative justice, health, entrepreneurship, and healing. Our focus is for all women to benefit from cannabis and hemp on their terms.

We hope the conversation ignited from our now-deleted post is not relegated only to social media but enters the public consciousness in such a way to inspire real change on the issues of cannabis legalization and drug policy reform in general.

Please continue to engage with us, as learning from one another is how women grow.

node.text:
Mixing Your Blueprint, Hustle, and Passion - A Game-Changer an interview with April Walker. 

This week, we are joined by April Walker, fashion game-changer, wellness advocate, disruptor, culture creator, author, speaker, and so much more. April was the first woman to create a streetwear brand that dominated in men’s urban wear, and made it’s own lane in the multi-billion dollar industry of fashion. April talks about the inspiration behind her first design in 1976, meant to design for her tribe and community in Brooklyn and to give them something to wear that they could identify with and feel proud of. Then, April discusses opening her first shop in 1987 and the challenges of being a woman in such a then male dominated field. 

April discusses how recognizing her pain point, serving her tribe, and finding the right dream team helped build a foundation to her success. April says she sees the similarities between of when streetwear was emerging to cannabis going legal. 

She talks about the energy of the Brooklyn scene and the legendary icons that have worn Walker Wear including Queen Latifah, Biggie, Run DMC, LL Cool J, and Mike Tyson in the actual boxing ring. Lastly, April discusses her interest in cannabis and her belief that taking a break is a powerful way to reset your body, mind, and spirit and come back even better. April’s book, Walkergems, Get Your A$% Off The Couch shares her business principles and motivates the reader to dream big. 

This is an interview you do not want to miss. @iamaprilwalker
